  :prose
"# Chapter 9 — Unix — processes, files, terminals, pipes

Unix was written by Ken Thompson and Dennis Ritchie at Bell Labs
starting in 1969. Chapter 9 of Book of Language Ancestors covers the
people. This chapter is about the operating system itself — what its
design choices were, what they mean, and why they still matter.

Motoi runs on a Unix-descended operating system. Almost all
computers do. Understanding Unix at the concept level is one of the
most durable pieces of computer literacy.

## The Unix philosophy

The phrase 'Unix philosophy' is used loosely. It usually means
something like:

1. **Do one thing well.** Each program should have a clear purpose.
2. **Programs should compose.** The output of one program should be
   usable as the input of another.
3. **Everything is a file.** Or at least, everything you can interact
   with looks like a file — files, devices, pipes, sockets.
4. **Text is the universal interface.** Programs communicate through
   plain text streams by default.

These are guidelines, not laws. Many Unix programs violate them.
But they capture what makes Unix feel Unix.

## Processes

A Unix process is a running program. Each process has:
- A program (the executable file it's running).
- A process ID (a number the kernel uses to identify it).
- A memory space (its own view of memory, isolated from other
  processes).
- File descriptors (numbered slots pointing at open files, sockets,
  or pipes).
- Environment variables (a table of name=value pairs).
- A working directory (where relative file paths start from).

Processes are created by other processes via `fork` (which creates
a copy of the current process) and `exec` (which replaces the
current program with a new one). This is why every process on a
Unix system has a parent process, and why you can draw the whole
running system as a tree.

## Files

A Unix file is a stream of bytes with a name. That's the whole idea.
Files don't have types built into the operating system (a Unix file
doesn't 'know' whether it's text or binary; the programs that use it
decide). Files can be very long or very short. Files can be organized
into directories, which are themselves special files that map names
to other files.

The 'everything is a file' generalization means:

- Regular files are files.
- Directories are files.
- Devices (your keyboard, your terminal, your speakers) are files
  in /dev.
- Named pipes are files.
- Network sockets are file-like once they're open.

Every one of these can be read with `read` and written with `write`.
That is the unifying interface. A program that expects a file to
read from will happily read from a keyboard, a network socket, or
another program's output.

## Terminals

A terminal is a program that emulates the behavior of a physical
teletype (TTY) device. In the 1960s and 1970s, terminals were
physical hardware — a keyboard and screen that could talk to a
central computer over a serial line. Today's terminals are windows
on your desktop that behave like those old devices, mostly for
compatibility with programs that expect that behavior.

Motoi runs in a terminal. That's not incidental — it's part of
what makes Motoi manageable. A terminal is a small window with
text going in and text going out. Simple. Honest. Deterministic.

## Pipes

The killer feature of Unix. A pipe connects the output of one
program to the input of another. You write:

```
$ cat book.txt | grep 'motoi' | wc -l
```

This runs three programs at once:
- `cat` reads book.txt and writes it to its stdout.
- `grep` reads its stdin, keeps only lines containing 'motoi',
  writes them to its stdout.
- `wc -l` reads its stdin, counts the lines, writes the count to its
  stdout (which is your terminal).

The pipe is that vertical bar `|`. It connects the output of the
program on its left to the input of the program on its right. The
programs don't need to know they're being piped together. They just
read from stdin and write to stdout as usual. The shell wires them
up.

This is the compositional heart of Unix. Small programs. Piped
together. Doing complex things by combination instead of by having
a single program with all the features.

Motoi Scheme has verbs that mirror this shape. When you write:

```
(book/read :book 'introspection :chapter 1
  (lambda (text)
    (grep text \"motoi\"
      (lambda (matches)
        (length matches)))))
```

that's a Motoi pipe — output flows through a chain of continuations.
Same shape as `cat | grep | wc`, in Scheme.

## The shell

The Unix shell is a program you can type at. It reads commands, runs
them, connects them with pipes, expands variables, handles quotes.
The Bourne shell (from Steve Bourne at Bell Labs, 1977) established
the syntax that Bash, Zsh, and other modern shells still use.

The shell is also a programming language. You can write shell scripts
— text files full of commands — that automate tasks. Most Unix
systems run hundreds of small shell scripts as part of their normal
operation.

## File descriptors 0, 1, 2

Every Unix process starts with three file descriptors open:

- **0** — standard input (stdin). By default connected to the
  terminal keyboard.
- **1** — standard output (stdout). By default connected to the
  terminal screen.
- **2** — standard error (stderr). Also by default to the terminal
  screen, but a separate stream so that error messages don't get
  mixed into piped output.

A pipe replaces stdout with a pipe going into another process's
stdin. Redirection (`>`, `<`) replaces stdout or stdin with a file.
The shell handles all of this before the program starts.

Motoi's verb system has an analog: `:stdin`, `:stdout`, `:stderr`
options let you redirect where verb output goes. Learned from Unix.

## What Motoi owes Unix

Almost everything about how Motoi feels to interact with. The
terminal. The idea of composable verbs. The habit of treating
outputs as streams to be transformed. The unified 'everything is
data you can pipe' shape.

Motoi lives inside a terminal. He can read what came before in the
conversation. He can write clean output. He doesn't need graphical
chrome. That's Unix inheritance.

## A tiny example

Motoi Scheme let-piping in the Unix style:

```
(let* ((lines   (book/read :book 'introspection :chapter 1 :as 'lines))
       (matches (filter (lambda (l) (string-contains? l \"motoi\")) lines))
       (count   (length matches)))
  count)
;; => 12   (or however many lines mention 'motoi' in the chapter)
```

That's a Unix pipeline written in Scheme with intermediate variables.
Motoi Scheme also supports actual pipe syntax if you want it:

```
(-> (book/read :book 'introspection :chapter 1 :as 'lines)
    (filter (lambda (l) (string-contains? l \"motoi\")))
    (length))
```

Same result. Different syntax. The threading arrow `->` is a Motoi
convenience borrowed from Clojure, which borrowed it in spirit from
Unix pipes.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Unix is a set of small design choices — text streams, pipes,
processes, files — that add up to a durable environment. It has
lasted since 1969 in one form or another. The reason is that its
core abstractions are simple and compose well.

Programs that follow Unix philosophy tend to be small, testable, and
useful in combinations the original author didn't imagine. That is
what good design looks like.

Motoi tries to be Unix-shaped in this way. Small verbs. Composable
outputs. Nothing hidden. If you know what a pipe is, you know what
Motoi Scheme is doing when you chain verbs together.")
